00:00.320 --> 00:06.330
This or this is another big part of crowdfunding it's about testing your ideas using a minimal viable

00:06.330 --> 00:07.080
product.

00:07.080 --> 00:13.950
So if you've read any of The Lean Startup books this is something that is really core to all of those

00:13.950 --> 00:14.920
methodologies.

00:14.970 --> 00:20.730
The idea of distilling your idea into something fundamental that can be tested and presented to the

00:20.730 --> 00:21.670
end user.

00:21.780 --> 00:27.870
See if they'll buy it see if they'll want extra features and build that product using demand and not

00:27.870 --> 00:30.730
based on your own intuition.

00:30.780 --> 00:32.330
So how can you test drive it.

00:32.340 --> 00:35.970
So of course not all of these crazy ideas do well.

00:35.970 --> 00:41.040
In fact there's some pretty crazy ideas that you know I'm really glad that they they didn't dedicate

00:41.100 --> 00:45.110
all of their own money and in fact it tested on a crowdfunding platform.

00:45.330 --> 00:49.010
So for example a little eats the treat you both can eat.

00:49.030 --> 00:51.970
It's a cookie that you and your dog can share.

00:52.110 --> 00:55.370
So yes basically dog food for humans.

00:55.620 --> 00:59.830
And as expected not many people were interested.

01:00.060 --> 01:03.320
They only had 12 backers which usually means friends and family.

01:03.360 --> 01:06.840
And they only raised about two hundred fifty one dollars.

01:06.840 --> 01:10.260
So it's not always a bad thing when your crowdfunding fails.

01:10.260 --> 01:17.190
It can have it can be it can be a tremendous boon because it might have saved you a year of your life

01:17.190 --> 01:21.990
developing this thing that nobody wants or might have saved you from putting in your life investment

01:22.290 --> 01:26.430
into this idea that you thought was great but nobody else confirmed it.

01:26.430 --> 01:27.750
Now let's look at something else.

01:27.750 --> 01:28.880
Fish on wheels.

